<TITLE> Cyprus court orders extradition of US fugitive </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NICOSIA, June 29 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - A court in Cyprus granted a US request on Friday to extradite a fugitive doctor accused of killing his wife with cyanide in 2005. Lawyers of the defendant, Yazeed Essa, 38, said they planned to appeal the ruling. They said he could face the death penalty if he returns to the United States and that his Palestinian origins could impair a fair trial. Both arguments were overruled by the Cypriot court. "I judge that all terms and conditions have been met for granting extradition," the judge said. American authorities have given assurances to Cypriot judicial authorities that Essa will not face the death penalty. Essa, an accident and emergency doctor from Cleveland, Ohio, faces aggravated murder charges over the death of his wife, Rosemarie, in February 2005. Rosemarie Essa had collapsed and died behind the wheel in her car in what was initially thought to be a traffic accident. A post-mortem showed she died of cyanide ingestion. Prosecutors allege she had earlier complained to a friend about feeling unwell, and that her husband had given her calcium pills to ingest. Essa was arrested clearing customs in Cyprus from Lebanon in October 2006. The couple had two childr
